BZ#14498: fix infinite loop in nss_db_getservbyname

nss_db uses nss_files code for services, but a continue on protocol
mismatch that doesn't affect nss_files skipped the code that advanced
to the next db entry.  Any one of these changes would suffice to fix
it, but fixing both makes them both safer to reuse elsewhere.

for  ChangeLog

	[BZ #14498]
	* NEWS: Fixed.
	* nss/nss_db/db-XXX.c (_nss_db_get##name##_r): Update hidx
	after parsing line but before break_if_match.
	* nss/nss_files/files-service (DB_LOOKUP): Don't "continue;"
	if there is a protocol mismatch.

Strip the values of DATADIR/MODULE_NAME in Makefile

This avoids potential issues with values containing spaces, and is
particularly important for the DATADIR variable.
Mention glibc 2.19, selecting supported file types in README

Support setting the NSS file types to support

Add a --with-types=FOO flag to "configure", with FOO being a comma-separated
list of file types to support, and use its value to determine which files to
build (in Makefile).

To maintain the original behavior of the module, the default value is set
to "pwd,grp".

Using "--with-types=all" will select all file types.

Remove files which are no longer needed

Now that the source files live under src/, remove the remaining
source files in the top-level directory.
Add config.mk to .gitignore
Import glibc-2.19 nss module sources

Merge remote-tracking branch 'origin/pr/1'

Merge changes in pull request #1, and accomodate for the fact that Eglibc is
no longer going to be developed after 2.19, namely:

- Change the "dlfiles" script to "updatefiles", make it download a tarballed
  glibc release and find the source files inside it. This is way faster than
  cloning the whole glibc Git repository.
- Keep support for honoring --libdir= in the configure script and Makefile

build-sys: Honor --libdir

This is necessary for Red Hat Enterprise Linux and Debian; which have
"multilib" and "multiarch" respectively that use e.g. /usr/lib64 and
/usr/lib/i386-linux-gnu directories.

Strip pwd/grp source down to just the parsers and add to build.

Now the altfiles module no longer depends on _nss_files_parse_*
functions in libc. Depending on those functions wasn't very proper
considering they are declared as GLIBC_PRIVATE.

After this change the only funky symbol from libc that altfiles depends
on is the _res_hconf structure. Unlike the _nss_files functions,
_res_hconf is explicitly declared as part of libc's GLIBC_2.2 ABI so I
feel a bit less dirty depending on it.

This replaces commit d6f2322f.
Import passwd and group file parsing code.

Explicitly link to libc.

Previously the library was linked using the -nostdlib flag which made
ldd --verbose look suspicious but everything still worked by virtue of
libpthread dynamically linking to libc. I don't know of any particular
reason for using -nostdlib and the documentation doesn't list it.

http://www.gnu.org/software/libc/manual/html_node/Adding-another-Service-to-NSS.html

Shuffle source files around into directories

This organizes things a little closer to the glibc source and avoids
clutter as I continue to add more things.

Compile all new file types, update CFLAGS

Fairly simple compile fixes:
 - Get better warnings (-std=gnu99 -Wall)
 - Add a few more includes and stub macros to compat.h
 - Fix symbol names in file-hosts.c
 - Fix the Makefile's build dependencies for included sources.

Import more file types from glibc 2.18.

Many of these such as networks, protocols, etc. make a lot of sense for
this module since they are usually never customized and thus have little
need to actually be in /etc all the time.

Correct logic around exporting and using external parsers.

Leaving this macro-glue untouched just happens to work for the mix used
buy the passwd and group types but breaks for others that I am adding.
Replace the existing logic only do 'static' or 'extern' but nothing in
between.

Define new ALTFILES_SYMBOL macros to replace CONCAT

The chaining of CONCAT macros was a bit ugly, this cleans up the changes
required to port files from glibc to altfiles.
